      "body" : "And if you want to document the compact format (something very useful I think), please write in the \"big comment\" the endianness of the mantissa and if ABCD are the 4 bytes of the compact number, which one is the exponent (A?) and which one is the mantissa (BCD in ?endian). As it is I think the format seems still \"black magic\".\n\nI'll add that you haven't really removed the internals of bignumber from the implementation: BN_num_bytes is based on the internal representation of BN. To make an example, BN_num_bytes of the 0 number is 0, while the .NET BigInteger serializes the 0 as a single { 0 } byte, and BN_num_bytes gives the length of the \"internal\" buffer of the BN, with the sign that is saved on another field, so BN_num_bytes(0xFF) == BN_num_bytes(-0xFF) == BN_num_bytes(0x7F) == BN_num_bytes(0x-7F) == 1.",
      "created_at" : "2012-09-17T09:44:23Z",
